People lament the cost of health care.

16:06.906 --> 16:09.796
They cry over soaring litigation costs

16:09.796 --> 16:13.505
and scream about the eroding 
integrity of our medical profession.

16:13.505 --> 16:17.083
The conduct of this doctor
and others like him are to blame.

16:17.083 --> 16:21.302
–Oh, lighten up, man.
–Mr Crane, you'll get your turn.

16:21.426 --> 16:23.262
We have rules.

16:23.262 --> 16:26.414
One is we do not go prescribing
experimental drugs

16:26.414 --> 16:28.632
that the FDA hasn't 
approved for market.

16:28.632 --> 16:30.548
Even if the patient consents?

16:30.548 --> 16:33.508
The patient will always
follow the lead of his doctor.

16:33.508 --> 16:36.501
For god's sake, look what 
people buy off infomercials.

16:36.501 --> 16:37.856
They'll try anything,

16:37.856 --> 16:41.574
hair potions, pills that make you
lose weight while you sleep.

16:41.574 --> 16:43.697
Desperate people will try anything,

16:43.697 --> 16:49.377
and when you have a licensed doctor
saying “here, take this,” they will.

16:49.377 --> 16:51.274
This isn't a potion.
This drug works.

16:51.274 --> 16:55.196
In preliminary studies, but there's
much, much more testing to be done.

16:55.196 --> 16:57.498
How long does it take the FDA 
to approve a drug?

16:57.498 --> 16:58.773
It isn't quick, but…

16:58.773 --> 17:00.368
How long?

17:00.368 --> 17:01.642
Nine years.

17:01.642 --> 17:03.656
My client's patient 
would be dead by then.

17:03.656 --> 17:05.226
But, hey, you've got your rules.

17:05.226 --> 17:06.737
–Objection.
–Oh, be quiet.

17:06.737 --> 17:08.673
Your honor, 
he can't tell me to be quiet.

17:08.673 --> 17:11.207
Let him have his turn, Mr Zale.

17:11.207 --> 17:17.433
You say that doctors shouldn't prescribe
non-FDA-approved drugs as a rule.

17:17.433 --> 17:21.420
–Yes. 
–Doctors don't prescribe medications

17:21.420 --> 17:23.925
for things that the FDA hasn't
approved them for.

17:23.925 --> 17:25.785
Off-label prescriptions happen, but…

17:25.785 --> 17:27.577
Doctor, have you ever prescribed a drug

17:27.577 --> 17:30.556
that wasn't approved for the particular
condition you were treating?

17:30.556 --> 17:32.293
–Yes, but…
–and, doctor,

17:32.293 --> 17:34.009
if you were overweight

17:34.009 --> 17:38.658
and at risk for an imminent
stroke or heart attack,

17:38.658 --> 17:43.020
is it your testimony that you would 
never consider taking Ramonibend?

17:43.020 --> 17:45.064
For myself, I might, but…

17:45.064 --> 17:47.816
but you wouldn't give your patient

17:47.816 --> 17:51.294
the same opportunity

17:51.294 --> 17:54.080
because you have rules.

18:03.150 --> 18:06.833
You're going to be the first lawyer sued 
by his client for sexual harassment.

18:06.833 --> 18:08.663
I'm a good lawyer because I got
a nose for the truth, Lori.

18:08.663 --> 18:12.024
You're attracted to her, Brad.
